[1
Date: 17 Oct 2001
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CBC, 17 Oct 2001 [edited
<http://www.cbc.ca/cgi-bin/templates/view.cgi?/news/2001/10/17/anthrax_011017>

U.S. Senate staff test positive for anthrax
-------------------------------------------
U.S. Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle confirmed Wednesday that 31 people
who work in his office have had positive nasal swabs for "exposure to
anthrax." Daschle said 25 of them are his staff workers, and the remaining
6 are members of the Capitol police force. He stressed that a positive
nasal swab does not mean the person has anthrax. Hundreds of people were
tested Tuesday after a suspicious letter was opened in Daschle's office on
Monday.
A U.S. health official said the anthrax exposure has been confined to a
"very specific area" of the Senate Hart Office Building. Deputy U.S. Surgeon
General Ken Moritsugu said only those who visited the building's fifth and
sixth floors needed to be tested for anthrax exposure. "At this time there
has been no evidence of (anthrax) spores in the ventilation system,"
Moritsugu said at a Capitol Hill news conference.
Speaker Dennis Hastert said people who work in the building were being sent
home until at least Tuesday so a full sweep could be done on the building.
Gen. John Parker, Commander of U.S. Army Medical Research says the anthrax
samples being tested are "pure spores" and that it is a "common variety
anthrax." He said they have not identified the particular strain at this
time.
[These were referred to me by Josie Buiza at CBC, which have the distinct
advantage of being brief informative reports. - MHJ
